    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_2",
    "text": "A-1 Yes, it does follow. Let P be any point in the plane. Let ABCD be any square with center P. Let E,F,G, H be the midpoints of the segments AB, BC, CD, DA, respectively. The function f must satisfy the equations",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.09586466560150368,
      0.16715116302252403,
      0.4906015095808188,
      0.22395833310452995
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001",
    "order": 3
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_15",
    "text": "A-3 The limit is 0; we will show this by checking that dn = 0 for all n ≥ 3. Starting from the given matrix, add the third column to the first column; this does not change the determinant. However, thanks to the identity cosx + cosy =2 cos *7} cos *Z', the resulting matrix has the form",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.5225564033571184,
      0.16715116302252403,
      0.9210526271691972,
      0.2519451485315607
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001",
    "order": 4
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_3",
    "text": "",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
