  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_17",
    "text": "with the first column being a multiple of the second. Hence dn = 0.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.5582706840012449,
      0.34300595242879106,
      0.9191729340438677,
      0.37080932157812224
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001",
    "order": 7
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_4",
    "text": "If we add the last four equations, then subtract the first equation and twice the second equation, we obtain 0 = 4f(P), whence f(P) = 0.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.12593985598307048,
      0.3561046510279427,
      0.49060151260400175,
      0.3998015874632723
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001",
    "order": 8
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_18",
    "text": "Remark. Another way to draw the same conclusion is to observe that the given matrix is the sum of the two rank 1 matrices Ajk = cos(j - 1)ncosk and B jk = - sin(j - 1)nsink, and so has rank at most 2. One can also use the matrices Ajk = e'(i-1)n+k), B jk = eilj-1)n+k",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.556346361536796,
      0.37645348882536567,
      0.9210526404235507,
      0.4652710074447214
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001",
    "order": 9
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_5",
    "text": "Remark. Problem 1 of the 1996 Romanian IMO team selection exam asks the same question with squares replaced by regular polygons of any (fixed) number of vertices.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.12781955019313804,
      0.4040178570295114,
      0.49060151260400175,
      0.4593023254296004
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001",
    "order": 10
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_6",
    "text": "A-2 Multiplying the first differential equation by gh, the second by fh, and the third by fg, and summing gives",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
