    "order": 11
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_19",
    "text": "A-4 The answer is no; indeed, S = Q\\{n+2/5|n EZ} satisfies the given conditions. Clearly S satisfies (a) and (b); we need only check that it satisfies (c). It suffices to show that if x = p/q is a fraction with (p,q) = 1 and p > 0, then we cannot have 1/xx - 1)) = n + 2/5 for an integer n. Suppose otherwise; then",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.5244360958020048,
      0.4781746032518327,
      0.9191729379072678,
      0.563988095280099
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001",
    "order": 12
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_7",
    "text": "",
