    "bbox": [
      0.21240601661402697,
      0.5116279077668313,
      0.3627819508671761,
      0.5290697670878199
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001",
    "order": 13
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_8",
    "text": "Write k(x) = f(x)g(x)h(x); then k' = 6k + 6 and k(0) = 1. One solution for this differential equation with this initial condition is k(x) = tan(6x + n/4); by standard uniqueness, this must necessarily hold for x in some open interval around 0. Now the first given equation becomes",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.12781954002757723,
      0.5391865081546998,
      0.49060151260400175,
      0.6238722937217629
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001",
    "order": 14
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_001_20",
    "text": "",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
